Spring Boot File Upload to AWS S3
=================================

How to build a Spring Boot application that enables users to upload files directly to AWS S3 storage, which is a scalable and secure alternative to local storage.

Step-by-Step Implementation Process
1. AWS S3 Configuration

Log in to the AWS Console and navigate to the S3 service.
Click Create bucket, choose a globally unique name, and uncheck Block all public access.
After creation, go to the Permissions tab and configure the Bucket Policy with a JSON snippet to grant public read access to your files.

2. IAM User Setup

Navigate to the IAM service to create a user for your Spring Boot application.
Attach the AmazonS3FullAccess policy to this user.
Generate Access Keys and Secret Keys; these are essential for the application to authenticate with AWS.

3. Spring Boot Development

Dependencies: Add the Amazon AWS SDK dependency to your pom.xml file to enable S3 connectivity.
Properties: Store your AWS Access Key, Secret Key, Region, and Bucket Name in your application.properties file.
Controller: Create a REST API with an @RequestParam of type MultipartFile to handle incoming file uploads.
Service Layer: Use the S3Client and PutObjectRequest classes from the AWS SDK to stream the file data directly into your S3 bucket.

4. Testing the Application

Upload Test: Use Postman to send a file to your API endpoint. You can verify the success by refreshing the S3 bucket in the AWS Console (6:40).
Delete Test: The video also demonstrates a delete endpoint that uses the DeleteObjectRequest to remove files from S3 by their filename (7:05).


